question.title: Will H.R. 33 (United States–Taiwan Expedited Double-Tax Relief Act) be enacted into law before May 1, 2026?
question.description:
Enactment would materially change the tax treatment of qualifying Taiwan residents’ U.S.-source income and would be a concrete signal of deepening U.S.–Taiwan economic alignment.

`{"format":"bot_tournament_question","info":{"hash_id":"83959a4628394b53","sheet_id":132.1}}`
question.resolution_criteria: This question resolves Yes if, after the time the question opens and before May 1, 2026, Congress.gov shows H.R. 33 has become law (e.g., “Became Public Law No: …” or equivalent enacted status) on the bill’s official page: [https://www.congress.gov/bill/119th-congress/house-bill/33](https://www.congress.gov/bill/119th-congress/house-bill/33). If Congress.gov does not show enacted/public-law status by the resolution time, the question resolves No.
question.fine_print: “Enacted” requires becoming law and public-law designation, not merely House/Senate passage. If Congress.gov’s status is temporarily delayed, use the latest available Congress.gov status as of the resolution time; if still unclear, Candidate Sources are: GovInfo bill-to-law publications and public-law records ([https://www.govinfo.gov/app/collection/plaw](https://www.govinfo.gov/app/collection/plaw)) and the “All Actions” tab for H.R. 33 on Congress.gov ([https://www.congress.gov/bill/119th-congress/house-bill/33/all-actions](https://www.congress.gov/bill/119th-congress/house-bill/33/all-actions)).
